<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910320-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>910320-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Court Orders Raytheon   To Pay $11 Million   To Volt Information</HL><DATE>03/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   RTN VOLT</CO><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The New York State Supreme Court orderedRaytheon Co. to pay $11 million to Volt Information SciencesInc. after it found the defense contractor misrepresented thecapability of a computer graphics business it sold to Volt.   The jury award in the fraud and breach of contract lawsuitcovers court costs, interest and expenses incurred by VoltInformation's Autologic Inc. subsidiary, which tried toimprove the product to make it marketable.</LP><TEXT>   Raytheon sold the computerized graphic design system forapproximately $2 million in 1983 to Volt, a diversifiedtechnical services and electronics manufacturing company.   Had the product measured up to Raytheon's claim, it wouldhave made Volt among the first, at the time, to offernewspapers computerized graphics in display advertisements.But the computerized component of the product could never bemade to operate commercially, explained Michael Hess, theplaintiff's attorney. &quot;If the graphics computer system hadworked half as well as the Patriot missile, we wouldn't havegone to court,&quot; he said during the seven-week trial whichended this week.   Raytheon may appeal the decision, a company spokeswomansaid.</TEXT></DOC>